            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers closing the Odyssey deal. The congratulatory emails flooded in as he stood in his SoMa penthouse, champagne untouched. The city lights glittered below, a sprawling circuit board he felt he'd mastered. Yet, the feeling was hollow, an echo in a life built of glass and steel. This moment, at 37, wasn't triumph; it was the chilling realization that he had optimized everything but his own happiness, planting the first seed of profound change.\n\n2.\nThe click of the front door was the only sound. He walked into the kitchen and saw it: her key, lying on the cold marble island. The silence in the high-rise was absolute, a vacuum where a life used to be. At 38, surrounded by the expensive proof of his success, he felt utterly bankrupt. That small, silver key wasn\u2019t just an object; it was the final, devastating metric of a life he had failed to properly build and the catalyst for burning it all down.\n\n3.\nThe first ferry ride home to Tiburon wasn't planned as a ritual. He just stepped on, exhausted after signing his new lease. As the boat pulled away from the FiDi, the cold, salty spray hit his face, and he watched the city\u2019s sharp angles soften into a blur. For the first time in years, he felt his shoulders physically drop. That 30-minute journey became the literal and symbolic passage into a life where peace, not position, was the destination.\n\n4.\nOne Saturday, he found himself chopping parsley in his new kitchen, the scent of garlic sharp in the air. He was trying to recreate his mother\u2019s chimichurri from memory, a taste of his Miami childhood. When he finally got the balance right\u2014the oil, the vinegar, the heat\u2014a wave of simple, profound pride washed over him. This small, sensory success, achieved in his early forties, felt more real and nourishing than any multi-million dollar spreadsheet he had ever built.\n\n5.\nHe was at a quiet waterfront restaurant in Sausalito, on his third date. He braced himself for the usual questions about his firm, his title. Instead, she asked, \u201cWhat were your parents like?\u201d The question sideswiped him. He spoke of his father's ledgers and his mother's history lessons. In that moment, he felt seen not as a Principal Consultant, but as Carlos, a son. It was a recent memory, but it reshaped his understanding of connection, teaching him that true intimacy begins where the resume ends."
